{{also|hộ lý|holly}}
==English==

===Etymology===
Old English {{term|halig|lang=ang}}; compare German {{term|heilige|lang=de}}. Ultimately from {{proto|Indo-European|ieh₂ǵ-|lang=en}}. Cognates include Greek {{term|ἅγιος|land=el}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈhəʊli/}}, {{SAMPA|/"h@Uli/}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|hōʹlē}}, {{IPA|/ˈhoʊli/}}, {{SAMPA|/"hoUli/}}
* {{audio|en-us-holy.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|əʊli}}
* Homophones: [[holey]], [[wholly]] {{italbrac|in accents with the [[wine-whine merger]]}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|holier|holiest}}

# [[dedicated|Dedicated]] to a [[religious]] purpose or T [[God]].
# [[revere|Revered]] in a [[religion]].
# [[perfect|Perfect]] or [[flawless]].
# Separated or set apart from (something unto something or someone else).
# Set apart or dedicated for a specific purpose, or for use by a single entity or person.
# {{context|slang}} Used as an [[intensifier]] in various [[interjection]]s.
#: '''''Holy''' cow, I can’t believe he actually lost the race!''

